<book id="jpa-dao">
    <bookinfo>
        <title>Data Access Objects (DAOs)</title>
        <subtitle>An Introduction to DAOs, DB Schema, and SQL</subtitle>
        <issuenum>${content.version}</issuenum>
        <pubdate>${docbook.pubdate}</pubdate>
        <copyright>
            <year>${copyright.year}</year>
            <holder>${copyright.holder}</holder>
        </copyright>
        <abstract>
            <para>This presentation provides and introduction to the Data Access Object (DAO)
                 pattern to encapsulate access to data, database schema used to design 
                 data organization in RDBMS systems, and SQL to access the data.
            </para>
        </abstract>
    </bookinfo>
    <preface id="jpa-dao-purpose">
        <title>Purpose</title>

        <section id="jpa-entitymgr-goals">
            <title>Goals</title>
            <itemizedlist spacing="compact">
                <listitem><para>Introduce DAO Pattern</para></listitem>
                <listitem><para>Introduce RDBMS Schema</para></listitem>
                <listitem><para>Introduce SQL</para></listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
        </section>

        <section id="jpa-entitymgr-objectives">
            <title>Objectives</title>
            <para>At the completion of this topic, the student shall</para>
            <itemizedlist spacing="compact">
                <listitem><para>have an understanding of:</para>
                    <itemizedlist spacing="compact">
                        <listitem><para>The role played by a DAO and business tier as it relates to accessing data</para></listitem>
                        <listitem><para>Core concepts to relational tables</para></listitem>
                        <listitem><para>How to define database tables and relationships using RDBMS schema</para></listitem>
                        <listitem><para>How to access data within the database using SQL</para></listitem>
                    </itemizedlist>
                </listitem>
                <listitem><para>be able to:</para>
                    <itemizedlist spacing="compact">
                        <listitem><para>Design the interface for a DAO</para></listitem>
                        <listitem><para>Create a schema in the database</para></listitem>
                        <listitem><para>Implement a basic DAO using EntityManager and native SQL commands</para></listitem>
                    </itemizedlist>
                </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
        </section>
    </preface>

